                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d458">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/600</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Liaison Officer</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                        >Wilson</hi>)<note n="25" xml:id="d458fn25">Addressed to the Chief of the
                        Division of Near Eastern Affairs (Ailing), the Assistant Chief of the
                        Division of Near Eastern Affairs (Villard), and the Adviser on Political
                        Relations (Murray).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-23">May 23,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At the meeting of the Liaison Committee on May 20, the necessity of sending
                    additional American troops to Liberia was discussed. The representatives of the
                    War Department stated that a construction force of over 1000 men is scheduled to
                    sail the latter part of this month. This force is armed with anti-tank and
                    anti-aircraft artillery, machine guns, rifles, and pistols. Consequently,
                    although these troops are primarily a construction force, they are also combat
                    engineers.</p>
                <p>The Under Secretary expressed the opinion that it would be helpful if President
                    Barclay could be discreetly informed of the expected arrival of this force.</p>
            </div>
